subsection.p:
We'll follow the example of 
and consider the 4 \times 4 case.
Suppose that A is similar to
 N = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} .
Using ,
we know that \inv{P} A P = N can only be true if


		A\uvec{p}_1 \amp = 0\uvec{p}_1 + 1 \uvec{p}_2 + 0\uvec{p}_3 + 0\uvec{p}_4 \text{,}

		A\uvec{p}_2 \amp = 0\uvec{p}_1 + 0 \uvec{p}_2 + 1\uvec{p}_3 + 0\uvec{p}_4 \text{,}

		A\uvec{p}_3 \amp = 0\uvec{p}_1 + 0\uvec{p}_2 + 0\uvec{p}_3 + 1\uvec{p}_4 \text{,}

		A\uvec{p}_4 \amp = 0\uvec{p}_1 + 0\uvec{p}_2 + 0\uvec{p}_3 + 0\uvec{p}_4 \text{,}


where the \uvec{p}_j are the columns of P, as usual.
Rewriting this to make it a little more clear, we have


		A\uvec{p}_1 \amp = \uvec{p}_2 \text{,}

		A\uvec{p}_2 \amp = \uvec{p}_3 \text{,}

		A\uvec{p}_3 \amp = \uvec{p}_4 \text{,}

		A\uvec{p}_4 \amp = \zerovec \text{.}


The effect of multiplication by A on the columns of P seems to follow a cyclic pattern,
though the pattern ends in the zero vector instead of wrapping back around to \uvec{p}_1.
This pattern becomes more evident if we repeatedly apply A to \uvec{p}_1.


		A \uvec{p}_1 \amp = \uvec{p}_2 \text{,}

		A^2 \uvec{p}_1 \amp = A(A\uvec{p}_1) = A\uvec{p}_2 = \uvec{p}_3 \text{,}

		A^3 \uvec{p}_1 \amp = A(A^2\uvec{p}_1) = A\uvec{p}_3 = \uvec{p}_4 \text{,}

		A^4 \uvec{p}_1 \amp = A(A^3\uvec{p}_1) = A\uvec{p}_4 = \zerovec \text{.}


Of course, the pattern ended at A^4 \uvec{p}_1 = \zerovec because A is 4 \times 4 nilpotent
().

statement.p:
Suppose A is a nilpotent n 	imes n matrix with A^{n-1} 
e \zerovec. To determine a transition matrix P so that \inv{P} A P is in elementary nilpotent form, choose a vector \uvec{v} in \R^n (or \C^n, as appropriate) so that A^{n-1} \uvec{v} 
e \zerovec, then form transition matrix P with columns
\uvec{p}_1 \amp = \uvec{v}, \amp \uvec{p}_2 \amp = A \uvec{v}, \amp \uvec{p}_3 \amp = A^2 \uvec{v}, \amp \amp \dotsc, \amp \uvec{p}_n \amp = A^{n-1} \uvec{v}.
A suitable choice can be to choose \uvec{v} to be a standard basis vector \uvec{e}_j when the 
th[j] column of A^{n-1} is nonzero.
